The government wants to reduce the torture of "witches", a brochure has been published.
In Burkina Faso, women who are declared witches have common traits.
They are part of the older generation, for example, they cannot work for health reasons, they are free and have no children.
The one who becomes a "witch" is isolated so as not to threaten the rest of the village.
"Man has very rarely this destiny".
"Young women who are healthy are also not judged because they work and give birth", says a sister who works in the capital of this West African country, Burkina Faso, in a special institution for more than 100 women who have been rejected by society.
The local government decided to intervene against this unusual "social measure".
He's published a booklet that should help limit the witch hunt.
There's a catch to this case.
"More than 70 percent of adults in Burkina Faso are illiterate", warned the newspaper Die Standard about the disadvantage of written education.
The accusation of witchcraft is common in other African countries.
In neighbouring Ghana, Ammy Hemma, a 72-year-old woman, died after being tortured by three women and a man and then burned with oil they had sprinkled on her.
The BBC server transmitted this information.
The criminals claim it was the evil eye.
According to their version, the oil used in the ritual anointing caught fire when the woman touched it.
The oil caught fire, they say, when the team tried to "chase the evil spirit" out of the woman.
Isolating "witches" is approved by people of all educational levels.
The newspaper Der Standard quoted a 42-year-old businessman in Burkina Faso as saying: "Eaters of human minds have always been a danger".
While Burkina Faso is working to reduce the witch hunt, Gambia has not seen the President himself participate in it until last year.
"Gambian President Dzammi, after the death of his aunt, launched a large witch hunt which allegedly contributed to her death and attempted to kill the President through black magic".
"Shamanists from neighbouring Guinea who came to the rescue brought to the presidential farm in Kanilai, under the protection of police and the President's personal guard, randomly selected men and women from villages in the Gambia", Amnesty International said in a message.
At the farm the prisoners were made to drink a herbal potion with hallucinogenic effects that caused other effects on the kidneys and intestines.
Two prisoners did not survive.
Under international pressure, about a thousand people were released.
The tenant of Bakal: the stoves are heating, he signed a higher rent.
A large elderly man walked out the door of the customer center of the RPG Byty company of "coal baron" Zdenek Bakal, the largest private owner of apartments for rent in the Czech Republic.
He was carrying a file under his arm with three new lease agreements for three apartments - his own, his daughter's, and his son who was serving time.
The deregulation has increased the rent for these three people.
Instead of paying 3,500, the son will have to pay from next year for a 2+1 second-class apartment 4100 crowns.
"And there is no hot water and the heating works on solid fuel", points to his son's new contract the man who has the power to sign.
"But I signed anyway", he explains, angry and half resigned.
The citizens' association of apartments BytyOKD.cz, which described the new rental conditions as "immoral and indecent", advises tenants not to sign and to wait until December 7, when a notice will be published explaining the method to follow to claim.
But the man responds to this with a hand gesture.
"One says this, the other says that", he frowned.
The Ostrava region is becoming a laboratory for deregulation.
After the New Year, this is what awaits most apartments in the Czech Republic whose rents do not match the market price.
Aktualne.cz therefore decided to visit the "laboratory" personally.
The RPG waiting room on Havirovska Street is one of four in the Ostrava region and it is already full on Tuesday morning at 09:00.
Right next to the door is a guard from a security company with a machine to call customers.
A special button, "rent 2011", is lit on the touch screen.
One press and a piece of paper with a number on it comes out.
You don't have time to read your number "157" because your number is already starting to shine on the big screen under the top of the waiting room.
In a split second, it's your turn.
After a short while, an old couple arrives to inquire about the rent, but the new rent does not seem to concern the people in the waiting room.
Most people came to settle common problems like everywhere else - claims for repairs, insurance events and so on.
In the Ostrava region, people in over 44,000 apartments in the RPG portfolio have been receiving mail with new leases in their mailboxes since about mid-November.
RPG Byty is offering them rent increases of 15 to 38 percent.
The special window for new rentals has been open to the public since 18 November.
"It's been working for almost a week, so it's still being tested", says the clerk behind the counter after a moment's hesitation when the customer introduces himself as a journalist.
The dredging and the former miners' apartments in Bakal are a very sensitive local issue.
The deputy speaker of the parliament from the Ostrava region, Lubomir Zaoralek, of the Social Democrats, made a rather strong statement about this before the elections and it is now filling the local newspapers.
"20 years after them, I want a new floor".
"They haven't even changed a fucking board in the bathroom", the man said.
However, the employees say that most of the people who come here are pensioners who want to be sure that they will get a refund on the new rent if they sign up now as RPG has promised in a special offer.
This is a refund of half the rent that will be paid to other tenants who have signed their new lease before December 15.
But the deregulation desk on Havirovaska Street is not really overwhelmed with questions.
"Of the 360 customers who came yesterday, only 40 to 50 came for rent", says the cashier.
And yet RPG has individual rent interviews on its website and in its storefronts when needed.
If the two parties do not agree on the rent, an independent court will decide.
'This is not a threat but only an informative way to act legally,' RPG says on its website.
"No one will go to court here", one of the employees of RPG Byty thinks, and the man on the street outside the customer centre proves her right.
"I have 13,000 crowns of pension and I have 5,000 crowns left to eat, I don't have enough to go to court", he said.
The employee suddenly feels uncomfortable.
"We'll see about that".
"Mr. Zaoralek in the media is asking that no one sign and so people are waiting", she says.
Rent regulation ends in the Czech Republic with the beginning of 2011 and the increases, according to RPG Byty, are an economic necessity.
"And, in addition, the current rents are still not at the level necessary for the simple maintenance of the housing fund", says Pavel Klimes, director of the housing portfolio at RPG Byty, who says that it is precisely the neglect of the housing fund that makes the tenant angry and is the main reason for the increase in rent.
However in 5 years between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able to invest in apartments with rents 4 billion, in four years from 2011 to 2014 it should be 5.2 billion.
The large screen hanging from the ceiling in front of the padded chairs in the waiting room on Havirosvka Street, however, repeats some information in red.
'The rent increase in 2011 is 15 percent and affects no less than 31,200 apartments or more than 90 percent of RPG's apartments.'
"And it will still be at most 7.50 CZK per square metre per month", the screen says.
The 38 percent increase is for just 400 apartments in the RPG portfolio.
"In these cases, this is an increase of a really low amount of 19.66 CZK per m2", adds RPG.
Next year, the rent will remain the same for 2,600 apartments.
RPG Byty promises that deregulation will not cause a radical increase but a gradual one over four to eight years.
It adds further commitments: all the money from the rent increase (see graph) is returned to the apartments in the form of heating savings - new windows and heating.
Those who sign the lease agreement have priority.
The kindergarten is also part of the offices, the architects included.
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch. Design.
No one would have expected it to also house a mini-kindergarten with everything you need - colorful walls, imaginative furniture, toys and finally a miniature playground on the terrace.
Since October last year, children of Arch. design employees have been able to visit.
The architectural project company Arch. Design, whose workshops have produced a large number of buildings in Brno, has been designing its mini-company nursery school since the first drafts of the Avriopoint building.
It employs about 90 people, mostly of childbearing age, and it was important to her that women architects and project managers could return to work quickly.
Alongside parttime work contracts, the nursery school is a bonus offered to its employees by the company Arch. Design. as part of its social programme.
This gives builders and architects the opportunity to combine demanding work with childcare.
The idea of this nursery school was conceived by the employees of Arch.Design themselves and with the support of the management they were able to obtain a grant from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The mini-kindergarten is financed by the European Social Fund through the Human Resources Operational Programme and the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
The financial allocations (CZK 2.8 million) enabled them to purchase equipment and apparatus and, after two years, to provide qualified staff and start-up.
After the use of the funding (two years) the company Arch. Design. is obliged after 3 years to operate the mini-nursery school from its own funds.
The preparation of the project took a year and it was the Economy rating company that helped to apply for funding.
The children are cared for by qualified staff, a nurse and a kindergarten teacher are on duty all day. Children can attend kindergarten without age limit but are usually over three years old.
Since it is a "mini-kindergarten", only 5 children can be present at a time, but during the day there are more who take turns.
The school is flexible in its operation according to the needs of the parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use the school regardless of their position in the hierarchy.
Although it is an individual care and education, the programme of the mini-kindergarten is comparable to that of pre-school education.
Children not only play here but also receive a quality education - from the beginning to school preparation, English is taught.
The classroom is equipped not only with imaginative toys and games but also with a computer for the children to use.
The presence of small children in society creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can monitor their child at any time and not have the stress of being late to pick up the children from a school far from where the parents work.
So parents use their work time in the most productive way.
It is not surprising that a natural bond of loyalty develops between employee and employer.
Arch.Design.is thus among the companies that offer a premium bonus for recruiting new employees and are family friendly and through this programme strengthens HR marketing.
The bone house still fascinates after 100 years.
The roof resembles the back of a prehistoric dinosaur, the staircase a dinosaur spine, and the balconies open fish mouths.
This is the case of the Casa Battlo house in Barcelona by architect Antoni Gaudi.
Because of its organic forms, the house was nicknamed the Bone House by the locals.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stones, fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade resembling scales and curves everywhere - these are all typical of Antoni Gaudi's Art Nouveau.
The front of the house has its dreamlike lines, pleasant colors and textures that remind of nature and animals.
When you look at it in more detail, you see the geometry, the rhythm and the order, thought out with precision.
At night the facade of the house becomes even more dramatic and is lit in such a way that the brilliant impression of the colors is enhanced.
The curling and twisting of the shapes also appears in the interiors to the same extent.
The wood is used to make window frames, railings, door decorations, eyelets, and slats.
The Battlo house which stands in the Eixample district on Passeig de Gracia shopping street at number 43, was born from the construction of an 1877 house by the architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The rebuilding took two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, Joseph Battlo, a wealthy entrepreneur, initially insisted on demolishing the old building and building a brand new one but quickly accepted Gaudi's idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
But the idea of Casa Battlo as a multi-apartment house was not the brainchild of Gaudi alone.
The architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It was precisely on his project that the decorations for an apartment representing the owner of the building and the use of mosaic for the facade were born.
Other artists and designers also worked on the façade.
The joint work for the plans of the Casa Battlo house began with a successful cooperation between Jujol and Gaudi.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudi's house Casa Mila and the Park Guell in which there are other works by Gaudi.
Locals nicknamed the warm house right after it was finished because of its organic shapes "the Bone House".
Others, because of the specific mechanism of opening the windows, have called it "the barking house".
It is said that at the top of the building there is a sword similar to that of St. George, patron saint of Catalonia.
Other sculptural elements of the building contain hidden religious motifs.
Gaudí designed a unique system for the house in his time of central heating, with typical ventilation fans and chimneys.
Their 45-degree inclination seems odd.
During the creation of the building Gaudi did not respect the building guidelines of the time and did not allow himself to be hindered by them.
At the beginning of construction he obtained the city's building permit, knowing, of course, that the data on the reconstruction plans were so vague that two years later during the completion the city council was horrified and asked for changes.
For example, the city council members were not happy that the pillars of the building were encroaching on the public sidewalk.
There was never any change, but on the contrary, only 15 days after the appeal by the city Josep Battlo requested (and was granted) permission to rent the two highest floors.
The owner moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a common living room and on the third a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The entire six-story house is divided by a staircase leading up to an independent roof terrace.
All right angles and straight lines were cancelled by the basic elements of the reconstruction and replaced by curved walls.
Gaudi also worked on the modern concept of connecting spaces.
The common area can be connected completely by opening the doors of the living rooms and the high society can communicate comfortably or limit the private space for more intimate conversations.
The house with Gaudi's reconstruction received in addition to new facades a non-traditional roof and two additional floors.
Gaudi's play with light is also impressive, with blue and white glass tiles decorating the inner courtyard and the light wells.
The two-color scheme provides maximum lighting in all floors of the house.
All you had to do was bet on the principle that white reflects more than dark, which absorbs sunlight.
The Casa Battlo house, which was inscribed in 2005 on the UNESCO World Heritage List, is open to all.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and splendid apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to take this step in 2002 to mark the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous designer.
They continued to visit because they saw that it was a lucrative venture and they expanded the scope of visits to the common areas and the attic including the roof terraces.
The entrance to the monument is really cheap, costing 16.50 euros, and students, pensioners, groups and tourist card holders get 20 percent discount.
The price is still above the price of admission to Gaudí's other buildings in the city.
If you want to feel the real atmosphere of the house with its fantastic turrets, you should quickly find a companion among the inhabitants of the building and tour the house completely.
How to choose a mattress and a mattress top: Women have different criteria than men.
No ostentatious setting, but rather the quality of the bed surface, so the mattress and the mattress bed provide a real base for a good bed.
Of course, they must complement each other harmoniously to please a particular user.
Several factors are decisive in the selection process: weight, height, age, health and gender of the owner.
The type of interior in which the mattress and mattress frame are to be placed is also important.
A typical example?
For example, in the country house where you do not sleep continuously, latex mattresses are not suitable because they warm up slowly.
They are also heavier than standard polyurethane mattresses.
It is necessary to turn them frequently.
If they also do not have enough ventilation channels in the core and if they are also on a solid board, they retain moisture and mold can also form.
Habit is also a factor in the choice.
If you are traveling abroad in the cold, often with very thick mattresses with a softening layer, you will not feel comfortable on a hard, low surface.
"That's how all the hockey players come home from the NHL complaining they can't sleep there".
"For their tired shoulders, feet and ribs, they needed mattresses with a softening layer of lazy foam".
"Such mattresses are also recommended for people with diabetes who have a nervous system disorder that causes them to misread 'information' from the joints and skin", says Sylva Adamczikova, a specialist in upholstered furniture.
That is why a few years ago the lazy foam mattress became a favorite among hockey players and other customers.
"Today everything is going well, Tempur, the Italian Magnifex but also the Czech Tropico have for example suitable mattresses.
You don't have to be an NHL guy to appreciate a lazy foam.
This "miracle" simply works.
It optimizes its rigidity and shape according to the heat absorbed or adapts to your body heat.
Nothing puts pressure on you and you won't look back into the night like you're out of a tough game.
You just sleep better.
The slothful foam also functions as a protection against squirrels.
To choose a mattress that is appropriate to your height, add the length of your feet, which is about 21/34 centimeters.
A man and a woman who are 180 cm tall need a bed of 210/220 cm.
The minimum width for each double bed should be 90 cm or 180 cm in total.
For single beds, for example single beds, it is recommended to take at least 120 /140 cm.
It's convenient in case of a visitor.
'However, there is a simple rule for the width of the bed: when you lie on your back, you should rest your hands comfortably with your elbows slightly bent.' Helena Prokopova, President of the Association of Bed and Breakfasts and Decorators who has been devoting herself for several years to the problem of healthy sleep and ergonomics of furniture and teaches it in specialised schools.
For a double bed, each person needs his own bed frame and mattress, so be careful when buying to choose the height of the mattress.
Otherwise, all you have to do is raise the tree to different heights, and this is not possible on all bed frames.
Foam mattresses should be at least 14 cm high, spring mattresses at least 15 cm, of which at least three cm should be counted for the form and airing layer.
"When touching or sitting on the mattress, you should not feel the springs", warns Helena Prokopova.
Each mattress requires a specific type of mattress.
The bed mattress, when the mattress and the bed mattress are joined like Siamese sisters, has no place in the bedrooms.
The mattresses are very badly rusted; you must not wash them, as is common today.
And since we normally sweat between 0.2 and 0.75 litres of sweat at night, it is clear that after 5/7 years the mattress begins to resemble a large (and stuffy) sieve.
So experts refuse to advertise a 25-year life for a mattress or a lifetime warranty.
But everything is at his mercy.
A practical tip from sellers: for a 120/140cm mattress, forgo hygiene or washing when covering the mattress, but add a protective mattress that you can easily remove and wash.
And although nowadays it is common to make coatings with zipper for the whole set, that is to say that after opening you have two parts (for washing and the size of the washing machine is very important!) otherwise the handling for large models (and for one person only) becomes when you remove them a fight between a lightweight and a heavyweight on a ring.
You have a hard board in your bed instead of a bed frame?
I never did!
Maximum for a bed for visitors for one night.
However, equip the board (if there are none) with air holes and use the spring mattress with a minimum height of 15 cm with spring bags (Germany Taschenfederken) and a layer of air.
A polyurethane mattress should not be part of a bed of this type.
For single-positioned slatted tops with 14/18 slats, latex mattresses or so-called sandwich mattresses (perhaps a combination of latex and coconut) are ideal but it will always be better for you to have a mattress with more slats, 28 and above, where the slats are folded in the lower part of the kidneys and thus it is possible to regulate the stiffness.
For multi-position mattresses, spring mattresses should not be used as they do not respond to changes in position.
In addition to adjusting the rigidity of the slats, a so-called shoulder cradle can also be installed.
This is a special bonding of the slats that allows the slats to be pressed or even tilted so that the sleeper's shoulder "fits" well.
For men who have "shoulders as wide as their backs", this is a really important thing.
This is already being considered by mattress manufacturers who have started using a softening zone at the shoulder for "male" mattresses.
But they also think about women - they give them a softer surface at the hip again.
For the more difficult customer there are wing or padded boots with what is called a multi-force suspension.
Pressure spreads to more points and reduces tension.
But of course, be careful, as soon as you use a bad pillow (big and inflated) on good mattresses and mattresses, the "plus" disappears.
The basic rule is a very simple pillow: the pillow should support the head and its tips should reach only the shoulders, so that the shoulder muscles can rest.
The recommended size is 50x60 cm which Scandinavians prefer per sample.
When lying on the side, the pillow should level the shoulder height (with the shoulder cradle of the summit or the softened area in the mattress).
Modern mattresses still have something in common with the earlier straw- and herb-based mattresses.
Manufacturers still use natural materials or mixtures.
The trend is also towards organic mattresses.
