Tracking devices are increasingly in demand among parents who want to monitor their children.
Fear for their children is causing more and more people to think about tracking them through a GPS.
The system, initially set up to search for cars, can also be used to track people's movements and help in some cases, such as that of little Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as big as a matchbox but will soon be the size of a watch.
The case of little Anicka moved many people and they began to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even if it means disturbing their privacy.
"We try to tell everyone that this is not espionage but just another way to reduce the likelihood of another tragedy", says Petr Pilin of MACRO Weil, one of the suppliers of tracking devices to the Czech market.
"I admit that there may be cases of misuse of such devices, such as putting them in the bag of someone who is not aware, but I have not yet encountered such cases".
"Most people are customers who actually buy the product for safety reasons", adds Pilin.
He said that children should always know what the box is used for and how to use it in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bockova points out that if a child does not want to wear such a thing, he will get rid of it.
'And even the youngest can be very creative when it comes to deliberately getting rid of something when they don't want to be in control.'
"Mobile phones, which can cut themselves like these tracking devices, have already made parents wait for long periods of time", says Bockova.
She said that the fact that this type of device can help in case of assault is highly questionable.
"If it is a premeditated kidnapping, the perpetrator will make sure that the child does not have an electronic device that can locate him".
"Now it's the phone".
"As soon as the tracking devices are developed, they (the criminals) will also be looking for them because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign".
"In such cases, criminals will always be ahead of the police", says the psychologist.
She admits, however, that such devices can help in the event of an unplanned assault by a pedophile.
Robert Cech of RC Monitoring, a company that provides tracking services for both cars and people, says that having this type of device can help, even if it is destroyed in the event of an assault.
'The apparatus may be configured to be in regular operation after a specified period of time.'
'In the event of the equipment being destroyed, the last position of the person concerned shall remain.'
'More expensive devices also have a tiltometer that immediately reports the position of the person who slipped and finds himself lying down without moving,' says Cech.
He said that so-called smart phones with a navigation system could provide a comparable service after being formatted with special software.
The problem with today's tracking systems is that they are either a device similar to the ones you wear in a matchbox-sized pendant or the smallest telephone devices.
We can always lose them.
Pilina of Macro Weil says that this is why tests are now being conducted to make devices that look like common digital watches.
"The advantage of this is that the attacker will not be able to recognize the tracking device".
"Or he will realize it after a while, which will give the police a little more time", he adds.
Whether the tracking device is developed as a bracelet or a pendant, it would still use the same technology as for tracking cars.
It is a combination of GPS positioning systems (commonly used in navigation) and a mobile phone function that alerts the vehicle's current position.
