At the Land Fund in Plzen, police made arrests during a public tender
In the building of the Land Fund in Plzen, the anti-corruption police have made arrests in recent days.
Detectives have handcuffed local real estate developer and dealer Lubos.
The Commission had tried to manipulate a public tender for the settlement of a refund claim in such a way that the proposed land was obtained by a specific applicant.
He was to pay Lubos G. half a million crowns.
"At the moment I can only confirm that the police are prosecuting a person for insider dealing in a public tender and competition", said the head of the Plzen prosecutor's office Antonie Zelena to the Pravo newspaper, knowing that he is not allowed to provide further explanations as the investigation is ongoing.
The police released the 46-year-old contractor after 24 hours.
How he could have influenced a public competition can only be speculated about given the limited official information.
When asked by Pravo, Lubomira Cerna, spokeswoman for the Land Fund, said that the police had actually made an arrest in Plzen at a separate workplace during the public tender.
"This was a customer and not an employee", she said.
The actual name of the public tender according to Cerna is 'Call for proposals for rights for the transfer of land under the Land Act' and is launched when several candidates are presented as rightful beneficiaries.
'These people are proposing, in the context of the appeal, a higher value of their rights to restitution which must be paid before the value of the land is announced.'
"According to the proposed rights, a ranking of buyers is established and the Land Fund then transfers the land to the person who has proposed the highest rights", explained the Fund spokesman.
Lubos G. clearly had information on the persons who had registered for the call and, as he himself is also a beneficiary, having bought a large number of refund rights, he had proposed to the candidates in the field not to participate in the competition.
And he probably got it by retiring.
Which would explain why he had so much money on him when he was arrested.
Lubos G. had contacts far above the standards at the FdT (Land Fund).
It was in the case of former FdT chief Vaclav Sankot who was prosecuted for publishing land for which a decision to set up a building had already been issued.
