Later he traded it with the town hall for a building in the historic center of the city whose value is far superior.
The city council was forced to accept because otherwise it risked jeopardizing the construction by blocking the land.
Households will pay an extra hundred kroner per month for the accommodation.
From January, households will have to pay extra not only for all types of energy but also for water and sanitation, heating supplies and in some places rents will also rise.
From January onwards, families will have to spend up to a hundred kroner more per month than now.
Electricity is up 4.6 percent, gas is almost 2 percent more expensive, in some localities you will have to pay up to a tenth more for water supply and in many places central heating supplies will also be more expensive.
The increase in electricity is expected to bring the annual cost of apartment households to about 100 kroner more than it is now.
However, all suppliers have lowered electricity prices in view of the development of renewable energy production, particularly photovoltaic cells.
Gas is rising moderately but of course at the time when people need it most for heating and therefore have the greatest consumption.
So we can also count a hundred crowns more.
Although electricity and gas are increasing throughout the Czech Republic, the change in the price of central heating differs from city to city.
The main ones planning the price increase are the larger municipalities.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Kraloce will pay almost 50 kroner more per month for central heating from January onwards, while families in Liberec will pay more than 1000 kroner per year.
For the inhabitants of Prague a 9 percent increase in water and sanitation is being prepared in case the city increases infrastructure rents.
If the rent does not change, the Prague residents will pay an extra 6.8 percent.
The price in Prague will still be among the lowest in comparison with the country as a whole.
In northern Bohemia, where prices are already among the highest, water and sanitation are rising by 7.4 percent.
The rents will rise significantly in the 450 000 apartments in rental from January, i.e. at the end of the regulation.
For example, the company CPI Byty, which owns almost 2500 apartments in Usti nad Labem, decided to increase the number of apartments by up to 100 percent.
Those who disagree with the new rent increase will be taken to court by the company.
The regulated rents people pay in almost 300,000 apartments could rise by 10 percent next year.
Czech children get drunk on rum and fennel, and beer is out of fashion and slow.
The fern, rum, vodka and, exceptionally, also the best brand of whiskey are stolen from the parents.
These are the drinks that most often bring those who get drunk, who are under fifteen, into the hands of the doctor.
Children who are treated in hospital for relapses are no exception.
This is evident from the experience of doctors who encounter similar cases in the children's departments of hospitals.
"Beers and wines are out of fashion because it takes time to get drunk".
'The trend is really towards strong alcohol,' says Ludek Pelikan, head of the children's department at the Horovice hospital in central Bohemia.
"When they manage to squeeze a bottle of dad out of the cupboard, it's sometimes whiskey but it's fernet and vodka that prevail".
"The advantage of vodka is that they can mix it with fruit juice and not smell it", says the head of the department.
Eva Jurinova, a spokeswoman for Motol Hospital, also agrees.
"It's usually rum or Fernet".
"Alcohol is the new trend, especially in elementary schools".
"In some cases, it was slivovice that they brought home", added Jurinova.
According to the Head of Department Pélikan, it is normal to see drunk children aged 13 to 14 in hospital.
Before he started working in Horovice last year, he was at Motol where he practiced for ten years in pediatrics where ambulances brought schoolchildren from the surrounding area completely drunk.
"A young girl was hospitalized four times like this
"She started her career at the age of 12 when she was brought in with 3.5 per thousand alcohol in her blood with a mixture of ecstasy", the doctor described this particularly important case.
"She was at the Holesovice Exhibition Park at a party".
"What is interesting is that the mother did not find it strange that her daughter was absent for 48 hours", said the Department Director in amazement.
It is the unselfishness of parents or their unusual tolerance of their children's drinking that is the main cause of the development of alcoholism in children.
However, according to experts, this is not strictly speaking a childhood addiction.
"Alcoholism is a chronic, multi-year addiction to alcohol with all the associated symptoms not found in children".
"In the case of repeat alcohol users, this is rather a significantly unfavourable socio-family background", explained Pelikan.
According to spokeswoman Jurinova, about forty drunk children were hospitalized this year until mid-November at the pediatric clinic in Motol.
Only cases with severe intoxication requiring hospitalization are included in the statistics.
Drunk children who are after emergency care brought home by parents or police are not counted.
Besides the cases of children sitting down and drinking a bottle of alcohol after school, there are three seasonal waves that Pélikan says can be expected: Witches' Day, New Year's Day and the end of the school year.
"Either they drink in spite of their poor results or they celebrate the beginning of the holidays".
"Of course I had a Witch's Day admission of seven drunk children at once", Pélikan said.
The drunk child who has spent the night in hospital in medical-supervised rehab is paradoxically better off than the one who goes home and has the "wood fever" the next day.
Morning headaches caused by dehydration and a lack of glucose are eliminated by infusing the body with glucose and nutrients it needs.
"They are better off because they have a good night and then they wake up feeling good and not hurting".
"They are just amazed at where they are", adds Pélikan, knowing that sometimes this spoils the patients' good mood at least with the bill for their care.
Ambulance transport and intensive care beds can cost up to tens of thousands of kroner.
"I have occasionally used this as an educational tool, telling these children how much their drunkenness cost them and how they could spend the summer working part-time to pay for one evening", Pelikan added.
However, he said, health insurance companies in their regressive approach, which should recover from parents the costs of care, do not treat cases of drunk children.
Two L-159 aircraft are in foreign hands for the first time in Spain.
Two of the five L-159s, which the Ministry of Defence has traded for Casa C-295M transport aircraft, took off on Tuesday for Seville, Spain, where the aircraft manufacturer Casa-EADS is based.
This is the first time that aircraft of this type have become the property of someone other than the Czech Army.
They have, however, been abroad for exercises or demonstration flights.
These are the two-seater versions of the L-159T1 which were until now in service with the Czech Army and were in flying condition.
The only remaining aircraft are single-seat versions of the L-159.
These are currently parked at Aero Vodochody and the commercial intermediary - the firm Omnipol - took them into account last week.
According to Jan Pejsek of the press department of the Ministry of Defense, the physical departure of the Vodochody planes is currently unknown.
'The L-159 single-seaters scheduled for exchange were taken from long-stored aircraft without causing additional costs or investment for the Ministry of Defence.'
"The two-seater L-159 T1 has been replaced in the state", said Pravo Pejsek.
