The Ministry of Defence did not launch a tender and contacted EADS directly.
The Defense Department argued that the exchange ensures future export of the L-159 overseas.
The Czech Army bought 72 aircraft from Aero Vodochody and uses only 24 of them, wanting to sell the rest.
The purchase of Casa planes will probably have legal implications.
The European Commission has, however, brought a complaint against the Czech Ministry of Defence before the European Court of Justice because the aircraft should have been selected through a European-wide tender and in no case by contacting a manufacturer directly.
The army has already taken delivery of three Casa aircraft, the last one is due to arrive at Prague Kbely Airport in two weeks.
A longer index finger than the thumb is a sign of low cancer risk
Men with a longer index finger than the ring finger are at a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the startling conclusion of a study published Wednesday in the British magazine Cancer.
It may depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our findings show that the relative length of the finger is a simple test of prostate cancer risk, especially for men under 60", said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, including by combining it with genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health history, Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009 she and her colleagues in Britain followed more than 1,500 prostate cancer patients and at the same time almost three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had the index finger of their right hand shorter than their thumb.
They were found to have the same likelihood of prostate cancer as the 19 percent of those with fingers the same length.
For those with a finger index longer than the ring finger, however, the risk dropped to 33 percent, while for men under 60 the risk decreased to 87 percent.
The ratio of the lengths of the two fingers - formed during the prenatal period - indicates, among other things, the different levels of sex hormones that the child is exposed to in the womb.
The lower the testosterone, the longer the index.
Previous research had shown that it is testosterone that contributes to the development of prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, told CTK that he was aware of the study but that he did not think the link between finger length and cancer was "fully demonstrated".
