The routine of democracy
Support for democracy in Latin America continues to grow, as does support for private enterprise.
Crime has become a bigger concern than unemployment.
And Brazil is seen as more influential than the United States in much of the region.
These are some of the conclusions of the latest Latinobarómetro survey of 18 countries, published exclusively by The Economist.
Since the survey has been carried out regularly since 1995, it tracks changes in attitudes in the region.
Two related elements emerge from the results of this year's survey, carried out in September and early October.
The first is the rather sunny mood of Latin America.
The second is the increasing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries around the Pacific Rim of South America (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% a year since 2002, support for democracy has fallen from a low of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also rose in Mexico, where the economy recovered after suffering a sharp drop in production last year.
But only about half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the region, are convinced democrats, which is lower than the regional average (see Table 2).
Some 44% of respondents in the region said they were satisfied with the way democracy in their country was functioning in practice, the same as last year but a sharp increase from 25% in 2001 (Graph 3).
Some 34% said they had confidence in their country's parliament and 45% in their government, the same as last year in both cases, but a sharp increase compared to 2003 (17 and 24%, respectively).
Ten years ago, economic problems in Latin America shaken support for democracy.
The fact that this has held up during the global financial crisis is certainly because many countries in the Americas have experienced a brief recession and have enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, a social security system has helped to protect the poor.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty increased only slightly in 2009 and fell again this year, to 32 percent.)
But moods vary considerably from one country to another (see Chart 4).
Brazil's good economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is reflected in a widely shared sense of progress.
This is rarer in Mexico and Central America where the recession has been more severe and violent crime has increased.
For only the second time since the survey began, more respondents across Latin America as a whole cited crime rather than unemployment as the most important problem for their country (see Table 5).
Some 31% say they or a loved one has been the victim of a crime in the past year; however, this figure is down from 38% last year and the lowest since 1995.
A more robust economic performance is reflected in increased support for private enterprise and the market economy: around 71% of respondents in the region say that private enterprise is essential for development, up from 56% in 2007 (see Chart 6).
Some 58 percent believe that a market economy is the only system that will make their country developed, up from 47 percent last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela are of this opinion (and 80% support private enterprise); even though their leftist president, Hugo Chavez, expropriates many private companies.
Brazil is the largest leader in the region, mentioned by 19% of respondents (down from 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged from last year) and Venezuela (9%, down 11% from last year)
But the United States is considered the most influential country by respondents in Mexico and most of Central America, while Venezuela enjoys this distinction in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
