Grammy nominations: Jazz singer Esperanza Spalding is a surprise selection in the "best new artist" category
Performed at the request of a president, and the people are required to be aware of it.
Esperanza Spalding, the 26-year-old jazz bassist and singer handpicked by President Obama to perform at his 2009 Nobel Peace Prize ceremony, marked one of the biggest surprises at this year's Grammy Awards with a major nomination in the "Best New Artist" category.
Considering that Spalding has been a well-known figure in the jazz scene since her 2008 album, "Esperanza", the nomination remains somewhat mysterious but is consistent with Grammy Awards rules that an artist must not release more than three albums before recording; this "establishes the public identity of that artist".
Her ambitious 2010 album, "Chamber Music Society", certainly marked a step forward, and given her slightly engaging vocal style, her skillful hand of pop and funk and her Latin influences, it is possible to draw at least a dotted line in Spalding's comparison to the meteoric success of Norah Jones in 2003, the closest equivalent for Grammy voters when taking into account jazz productions in this category in recent years.
Elsewhere, the Grammy voters rightly honored Vijay Iyer Trio's "Historicity" in the "instrumental album" category, a departure from the refreshing thrill of a recording that was a top favorite last year.
Among the Iyer, "Moody 4B" by veteran saxophonist James Moody and "Positootly" by keyboardist John Beasley will be in competition.
Trombone Shorty, a favorite with a raucous voice from New Orleans and a frequent guest on HBO's "Treme", was honored in the Contemporary Jazz category; which also leans heavily toward a sure fusion with albums by Stanley Clarke, John McLaughlin and Jeff Lorber.
Wild Darcy James Argue's Secret Society, familiar with steampunk, won some well-deserved accolades in the big ensemble category; competing with the rich chamber jazz of Billy Childs Ensemble and the eternal adventurer Dave Holland whose album "Pathways" from his octet's live was a fine example of this bassist's democratic hand as a bandleader.
Grammy nominations: Michael Daugherty and Steve Mackey lead in classical categories
The classic nominations for the 53rd Annual Grammy Awards feature a mix of landscapes from musicians and composers from around the world.
Top nominations included "Deus Ex Machina" by Michael Daugherty, for piano and orchestra, with five "yeses"; and "Dreamhouse" by Steve Mackey, an electric orchestral work, with three "yeses".
Among the nominees with ties to Southern California is Estonian composer Arvo Pärt for his Symphony No. 4, "Los Angeles", a work that was commissioned by the Los Angeles Philharmonic and opened at the Walt Disney Concert Hall in 2009.
The Madolin Concerto by Los Angeles-based composer Avner Dorman is also in the running for an award.
The classical nominations are divided into 13 categories covering orchestral, opera, choral and solo recordings.
A category for classic producer of the year features five nominees: Blanton Alspaugh, David Frost, Tim Handley, Marina and Victor Ledin and James Mallinson.
Nominations for the classical album are Bruckner's Symphonies Nos. 3 and 4 from the Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra; Daugherty's "Deus Ex Machina" and "Metropolis Symphony" from the Nashville Symphony Orchestra; Steven Mackey's "Dreamhouse" from the Boston Modern Orchestra Project and Synergy Vocals; "Sacrificium - the Art of the Castrati" featuring various artists; and Verdi's "Requiem" from the Chicago Symphony Orchestra and Chorus.
In the opera category, the nominees are Berg's "Lulu" from the Orchestra of the Royal Opera House, Adolf Hasse's "Marc Antonio e Cleopatra" from the Ars Lyrica Houston; Kaija Saariaho's "L'Amour de Loin" from the Deutsches Symphonie-Orchester Berlin; Rodion Shchedrin's "The Enchanted Wanderer" from the Orchestra and Choir of the Mariinsky Theatre; and Arthur Sullivan's "Ivanhoe" from the BBC National Orchestra of Wales.
Composers who are up for the Grammy Awards for contemporary composition include Pärt for Symphony No. 4, Daugherty for "Deus Ex Machina", Hans Werner Henze for "Appassionatamente Plus", Magnus Lindberg for "Graffiti" and Shchedrin for "The Wanderer Enchanted".
Pärt's Symphony No. 4 premiered at Disney Hall in January 2009 in a performance recorded by the Los Angeles Philharmonic Orchestra, conducted by Esa-Pekka Salonen.
The piece, which lasts about 30 minutes, is called "Los Angeles" and is dedicated to the former oil tycoon Mikhail Khodorkovsky, imprisoned in Russia.
Dorman's "Mandolin Concerto" was nominated for its solo instrumental performance with an orchestra.
The Los Angeles composer said he wrote the 15-minute piece specifically for mandolin player Avi Avital, who performed the concerto with the New York-based Metropolis Ensemble.
"I wrote it using Middle Eastern sounds and a lot of North African scales and rhythms", Dorman said in a telephone interview.
Conductor Pierre Boulez, 85, received a nomination in the orchestral performance category for conducting the Chicago Symphony Orchestra in a recording of Stravinsky's works.
Among the instrumental soloists who received nominations were pianists Nelson Freire and Marc-André Hamelin; organist Paul Jacobs; violinist Julia Fischer; and harpist Sarah Schuster Ericsson.
This year, there are only nominated solo vocalists; they are: Anne Sofie Von Otter, Cecilia Bartoli, Lucie Duchonová, Vivica Genaux and Measha Brueggergosman.
In the classical mixing category, soprano Jessye Norman received a nomination for her recording of "Roots: My Life, My Song".
