A microbe that tolerates arsenic raises the possibility of new life forms on Earth, or elsewhere.
The discovery of a strange bacterium, which can use arsenic as one of its nutrients, expands the field to find new life forms on Earth and perhaps beyond.
Although researchers have discovered the unusual bacteria here on Earth, they say it shows that life has possibilities beyond the major elements that have been considered essential.
"This organism has double capacity".
"It can grow with either phosphorus or arsenic".
"That's why it's so special, even though it's far from a truly 'alien' life form", said Paul C. W. Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of the report in Thursday's online edition of the journal Science.
Six major elements have long been considered essential for life - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus, and sulfur.
But researchers have discovered that the bacteria, discovered in Mono Lake, California, is able to continue growing after replacing the phosphorus with arsenic.
"We wonder what else is possible", said Ariel Anbar D. of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
The discovery is important in the search for life beyond Earth because researchers must be able to recognize life, to know what life looks like, Anbar says.
The study focuses on a microbe found on Earth.
However, the announcement of a press conference to discuss the find, which did not disclose the details of the find, has generated widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could reveal the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
It was not.
The discovery "shows that in other planetary environments organisms may be able to use other elements to drive biochemistry and that the 'standard' set of elements, which we believe are absolutely necessary for life, may not be fixed", said Charles Cockell, professor at the Institute of Planetary and Space Science Research, Open University, Milton Keynes, United Kingdom.
Cockell wasn't part of the search team.
"This work is new because it shows the substitution of one element for another in basic biochemistry and biochemical structure", Cockell added.
It wasn't a chance discovery.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Institute of Astrology, who led the study, chose Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, so she speculated that a microbe exposed to both substances might be able to substitute for one.
"Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is very similar to that of phosphorus".
"As a result, the organisms have difficulty distinguishing these elements separately".
"But arsenic is different enough that it does not work exactly like phosphorus; it penetrates inside and, in a way, gums the work of our biochemical machine", Anbar explained.
The researchers collected the bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed it to increasing concentrations of arsenic, which allowed it to adapt and grow.
The microbe grows better with phosphorus, but the fact that it can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that a life form using arsenic could occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said that the idea that arsenic could be replaced by phosphorus was not new, but there was no evidence that it could work.
Arsenic was more common in the early days of Earth's existence, she says, so researchers have hypothesized that early life forms may have used it.
This suggests that there could be other ways of forming life, not just the way life on Earth was formed at first", said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was funded by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institutes of Health.
