The lion is ready to roar again, MGM restructuring just waiting for final green light from the court
After 18 months of turbulence and uncertainty, MGM finally got the green light to start over.
A federal bankruptcy judge in New York officially praised on Thursday the creditors' "pre-packaged" plan to cancel about $5 billion in debt, paving the way for the 86-year-old entertainment company to focus its efforts on film and television production and distribution.
With Thursday's ruling that the plan meets the requirements of the U.S. bankruptcy code, there are no legal barriers left for MGM to float back under the tutelage of Entertainment Spyglass founders Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, who will become the chief executives of what will be a slim studio.
The staff will be reduced to about 320 from 400 initially.
MGM will not actually emerge from Chapter 11 until JPMorgan Chase has closed a $500 million credit facility to fund MGM's new operations and production.
It is currently being licensed by the investment bank, which is itself facing $75 million, and is expected to be funded by mid-December.
The restructuring process of the studio began in May 2009 when the investment bank Moelis & Co. was hired to advise management on how to invest its finances as it could not afford to pay the interest of $300 million per year.
In August, the CEO, Harry Sloan, was replaced by Stephen Cooper, a former Enron CEO and recovery expert known for his work at Krispy Kreme Doughnuts.
Moelis and Cooper's attempts to resolve MGM's financial difficulties and satisfy the studio's more than 140 creditors took much longer than expected.
After several months of discussions, the parties agreed at the end of 2009 to sell the company.
However, the auction attracted few bidders, and none of them were willing to pay the additional $2 billion that creditors were seeking.
In the spring of this year, everything had to be done over again as the MGM team began work on a restructuring plan which, after months of internal disagreements and debate, was finally approved by the creditors in late October.
When MGM officially emerged from bankruptcy in the following weeks, Moelis and Cooper's companies received multi-million dollar bonuses for their work.
Moelis & Co., which has already obtained $1.2 million, will receive a payment of $9.5 million.
Cooper's companies, which have raised $375,000 a month for their business management services, will receive a $4 million "success bonus".
Barber and Birnbaum plan to revive production at MGM, which released only one film this year, and put together an annual list of seven or eight films that would be released starting in 2012.
They also intend to co-finance two films based on The Hobbit, with Warner Bros.
The studio must take out a separate loan of between $265 million and $275 million to finance its share of these two films, which are to be directed by Peter Jackson.
Investor Carl Icahn, who owns about 18% of MGM's debt, attempted to achieve a merger of the studio with Lions Gate Entertainment, where he is the major shareholder.
However, recent discussions between the two companies have not resulted in an agreement.
