Bringing a Softer Side to Law Enforcement in China
Tang Shenbin walked through a city square like a city sergeant in training, scrutinizing his nerve charges, giving orders in a low voice with military authority.
He wanted the female members of chengguan - imposing public order officials in China, feared and despised for their arbitrary repression and penchant for violence - to convey a certain impression to a group of spectators.
"Stand up straight!"
"Be sharp!"
Show them, he says, "what pretty girls look like".
Four girls in white gloves, identical olive-colored jackets and pants, just past their teenage years, were standing on guard duty.
Four pairs of black heeled shoes, aligned to the rule.
Four neat hats perched perfectly on top of hair tied in a blue and white striped knot.
"Personally, I think they look average", said Mr. Tang, disdainfully.
"The models are pretty".
More than one government has tried to refresh the image of China's urban inspectors.
One city required that all new recruits have a college degree.
The province of Guangdong has replaced the gray-green uniforms with a supposedly more engaging blue.
Wuhan, central China, has replaced the eye-rolling with the strong way: In 2009, a report reported that 50 officers surrounded an uncontrollable snack cart with black eyelashes, firmly for half an hour, until the mailman packed up and left.
Xindu, an urban district of 680,000 in Chengdu, chose to do a big image operation.
Since 2003, the district has supplemented its urban street police with 13 women, specially selected for their appearance, their complexion and their young age.
The idea is to give the police a softer, more feminine side.
Unfortunately, even Scarlett Johansson may have trouble getting attention for this underground urban brigade from China.
And for good reason, critics will say.
Unlike the police, these officers are only authorized to enforce municipal ordinances by imposing fines or other administrative sanctions.
But the Chinese media portray the news in a different reality.
In January 2008, inspectors in Hubei province beat a spectator to death after he used his mobile phone to film them dispersing a protest against a landfill.
Last year, a training manual for Beijing detectives was stolen and posted online, describing how to effectively defeat criminals without bloodshed.
This year in Shanghai, a watermelon peddler was abandoned with a brain injury after a fight with five officers.
A violent video game, available for download online, shows Chinese detectives trained to assault street vendors.
"Chengguan has left a mark on the government", lamented China Daily, a national publication, after another controversy over tactics last year.
The paper called for a "true and complete cleanup".
Skeptics say the approach is far from it.
After the district announced in October that it was looking for eight new female recruits, an editorial in The Beijing Evening News asked whether the women had real jobs or were just a tourist entertainment.
The answer seems to be a little bit of both.
The district's advertisement required female candidates, aged 18 to 22, to have a beautiful figure and "the five facial features in the correct order".
They must be above average height, or 5 feet, 2 1⁄2 inches.
Retirement at 26 is compulsory.
The officers said the work was too physically demanding for women over 25.
"It's their image that matters", a district officer told Rednet.com, a quasi-governmental website.
"First, the external qualities of the candidates will determine their suitability - height, weight, facial features, etc".
Then there are temperament and "inner qualities".
Chengguan women are like flower pots, he said, adding: "In addition to being pots, they will have other responsibilities.
Zheng Lihua, deputy director of the city's district management office, does not agree with this description.
But he noted that height requirements were the standard standard in many Chinese job offers for both sexes.
This is the case with the requirement for the order of facial features.
What that means beautiful is a matter of debate among the Chinese.
Of course, disabled or disfigured persons do not have to apply.
"We cannot allow a lame or a hunchback to come here to serve", says Mr. Zheng.
"It wouldn't look good".
Liu Yi, who patrols Baoguang Square near a monastery, is 22 years old and has a cheek patch with a finely curved mouth.
She doesn't consider the highlighting of her appearance to be sexist, she said.
"Do you think I look sexy in this uniform?" she asked with a disillusioned look.
Xu Yang, a 21-year-old colleague at the pits, says: "Our job is to present the image of the city".
They said they were not opposed to having their terms limited because they had higher career ambitions than simply driving the vendors out into the alleys where they are supposed to limit their activities.
Every morning, the team faces a dozen street vendors who move quickly on foot or by bicycle, trying to sell as many loaves or bowls of tofu as possible before fleeing.
"Master Wang, you must leave".
"We've told you many times before!" said Ms. Xu as one vendor fled on foot, temporarily abandoning his bicycle-loaded noodle cart.
Officers describe their duties as monotonous rather than arduous.
"It's about the same thing every day", said 20-year-old Huang Jing, who studies marketing after work.
"Great routine".
One reason is that female agents do not have the power of their male counterparts to seize the goods of the sellers.
They can only threaten to report offenders to their male superiors.
This tends to protect them from the sudden public displays of animosity against bureaucracy that are common throughout China.
This year, hundreds of citizens in Kunming, the capital of Yunnan Province, revolted after false rumors spread that Chengguan agents had killed a vendor.
In one night, more than a dozen police and Chengguan agents were injured, 14 government vehicles were overturned or set on fire.
Xindu has so far escaped such violence.
But there is little guarantee of peace.
Just two blocks from the quiet Baoguang Square, where the female officers were patrolling that morning, more than 50 people gathered on the street corner.
Officers confiscated a motorcycle that was being repaired on the sidewalk instead of in a shop, as required by the regulations.
