Justice Department prosecutors have dropped criminal charges against Senator John Ensign, stemming from a case involving a former campaign aide and his efforts to secure a lobbying job for the woman's husband, the senator's lawyers said Wednesday.
The ruling ends the most serious legal threat facing Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was considered a possible Republican presidential candidate in 2012 until the scandal surrounding his case made national headlines last year and hurt his career.
Mr. Ensign's office said it was "very happy" with the decision, the result of a year-long investigation.
The senator could still be subject to disciplinary action by the Senate Ethics Committee.
Mr. Ensign's lawyers said the Justice Department had "informed that Senator Ensign is no longer under investigation and that it does not intend to pursue any charges against him in this matter".
The Ministry of Justice declined to comment on the matter.
The announcement came as a bit of a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Justice Department, who said there would be significant evidence indicating that Mr. Ensign conspired to violate a federal criminal ban on lobbying.
Interviews, emails, and other documents, first released in October 2009 in The New York Times, indicated that Mr. Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, obtain a lucrative lobbying job to silence Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the senator's affair with her.
Mrs. Hampton once served as treasurer during an Ensign campaign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political funders to find work for Mr. Hampton and then he defended their rights after they hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them, according to the documents and interviews.
Since Mr. Hampton had recently been an associate of Mr. Ensign, he was prohibited by law for one year from lobbying his former employer or the Senate as a whole.
Ethics experts have argued that the unusual agreement between Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were close friends before the case, seems to contradict the so-called revolving door ban on lobbying.
From the evidence that has been released, "there appears to be prima facie evidence of a conspiracy to violate and a substantial violation of the revolving door law", said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer specializing in defending clients from a government investigation.
Although the department's judge declined to explain the reasoning that led to the Ensign decision, Brand and other ethics lawyers said the department appeared wary of political prosecutions after a number of high-profile setbacks by its public integrity section, including a decision last year to drop charges against former Sen. Ted Stevens on charges of misconduct.
Federal prosecutors are clearly afraid to take up arms, said Melanie Sloan, executive director of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, an advocacy group that has received several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
"This basically says high-ranking government officials can now assume the laws do not apply to them", she added.
Paul Coggins, Ensign's lead lawyer, said in an interview that he received a phone call from a Justice Department prosecutor on Monday and a follow-up the next day, telling him the department was not seeking charges against his client.
Mr. Ensign's legal team had cooperated with prosecutors in trying to persuade them that the senator, as his office reaffirmed in a statement Wednesday, "had acted in accordance with the law".
Mr. Coggins refused to elaborate on the legal arguments he made to the prosecution.
"I'm not comfortable going into the details of my discussions with the Justice Department, except to say that we think they made the right decision", he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to drop an investigation following an independent complaint by the ethics group, alleging that the payment of $96,000 by Mr. Ensign's parents to the Hamptons violated federal election law.
The election commission said they didn't have enough evidence to prove the money was anything but a gift.
Energy NV, a major Nevada corporation that has long supported the senator, is a company that Mr. Ensign helped Mr. Hampton find lobbying work for.
