Can civility bridge the gaps?
After a campaign marked by invective and negativity, a minimum of civility has broken out in Washington this week.
Is this a harbinger of real bipartisan cooperation going forward or an illusory moment before the rapid return to partisan struggle in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders produced no breakthrough on the big issues that must be addressed during the lame duck session.
But obviously, at least there was a polite discussion about the differences between the two sides as well as the recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another episode where each side wanted to score points.
Wednesday's public meeting of the chairman's deficit committee was just as civilised, despite the political differences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created mutual respect that transcends the ideological divide, but which, however, still divides the members.
This is hardly enough to declare a new era of cooperation.
Both sides are now in a period of testing and testing each other for signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and voters' patience for renewed guerrilla warfare.
That is why Tuesday's meeting and subsequent comments from participants revealed a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too big and too deep to suggest a rapid climate change that has existed in the last two years.
Whether it's taxes, expenses, health care, or rights, the two parties stay miles apart.
Yet the November election had moderated Washington, at least in the short term.
"There's no doubt that things have changed in tone", said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now with the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
"It's inevitable after the election.
Elections arouse partisan passions and then they fade away.
That's good".
On some issues, including those on the agenda of the lame duck session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax cuts are due to expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of that.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve some or all of it, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a compromise is possible on the extension of unemployment benefits, if only because the Republicans cannot afford to appear to be in favour of tax cuts for the rich while denying unemployment benefits to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's White House meeting, more optimism is looming over a possible agreement on the issues raised during the lame duck session, with the ratification of the New START pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on the most pressing issues of the lame duck session may not prevent better understanding between the two parties when the 112th Congress meets in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is likely, if not inevitable.
"Once the things that need to be done will be done, psychology in the short term will return to one of the confrontations", he said.
Wehner also expressed his widely shared skepticism that civility would lead to true cooperation.
"I consider most of what happens between now and 2012 as a pre-show or a shadow-boxing in relation to the main event of 2012", he said.
The reasons for this are closely linked to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters at the tea that helped create it.
But Republican leaders are aware of the dangers of going too far, they know they have to try to live up to their promises to cut public spending and repeal the new health care law.
These partisan positions are already clear in the first reactions to the recommendations of the deficit committee, which include reforming the tax code and raising certain taxes, pushing back the retirement age and cutting spending.
Co-Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have chosen one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and have, in their view, placed the deficit issue on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the committee, which has 18 members, to make their plan an official recommendation, and they've had a hard time getting that number.
The greatest resistance remains among the group's elected representatives, suggesting that there is little motive or willingness to compromise on tax matters, at least for the time being.
Galston foresees two phases in the fight between the White House and the Republicans in Congress.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan clashes, as Republicans challenge Obama on budget, taxes and health care; then followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would cause the change?
The public opinion.
There is ample evidence that despite the partisan spirit of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see both parties work together.
If the confrontation leads to a stalemate, as in 1995, then both parties will watch the public reaction carefully.
The one who loses must change course and compromise.
But that would still be an optimistic view.
Partisan sentiment and polarization is greater today than it was in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a greater ideological divide between Obama and the Republicans in Congress than there was then between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as merely a prelude to a larger election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civility on display this week could be appreciated by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on the part of both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
