It is actually a powerful process simulation software that the German company launched on the market in 2007 with objectives far removed from high-level automotive competition.
Called PLM, this powerful computer tool has been used to create assembly lines for manufacturing plants around the world, power plants, high-precision instruments.
The aim is to reproduce, simulate accurately the product or process before building it in a real way, thus avoiding avoidable defects and costs.
PLM has facilitated the development of Canon cameras, Sukhoi aircraft or Nissan's most famous commercial vehicles.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of Siemens' industrial division, explains that the use of this computer instrument in its Formula 1 factory allowed Red Bull to create and execute "within a few hours, almost in real time", the modifications, changes and improvements detected during races and testing.
Russwurm explains that the 1992 teams had an average of 10 technicians in their teams who were able to introduce a maximum of three or four improvements to the vehicles each season.
The Red Bull team now has 180 highly qualified young professionals who, equipped with powerful computer equipment, analyse and design all kinds of modifications to the cars.
The Siemens executive explained that the PLM software is capable of analysing and improving all the elements of Red Bull cars except the engine, which is the sole responsibility of Renault.
The materials, the fuel, the aerodynamics and the safety elements are modified.
Changes can be made from simulator to virtual reality in less than 24 hours, thanks to advanced laser production systems and high-tech autoclaves.
The only limitation to this madness of technological improvement is the amount of $40 million that each Formula One team can spend as a limit each season to facilitate competition.
Red Bull has set up the high-tech factory to design and produce its cars in a town 30 miles outside London.
These are two buildings where visits, especially for journalists, are restricted.
Everything that happens in there is classified.
The staff for this task is 580 people, including two drivers, champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
The hero of Red Bull's Formula One, without a doubt, is the recent champion Sebastian Vetell.
Among the immense technological resources that the energy drink brand has put at the service of its participation in the circuits, there are other hidden protagonists, whose activity is invaluable and notoriety zero.
The factory's chief technology officer, Steve Nevey, says that five years ago it could be said that progress in R&D in the case of racing cars was responsible for 50 percent of the wins and the drivers were responsible for the rest.
