Zapatero and the German Red Line
Berlin has chosen to remain in the euro, but it has set the conditions for the whole Union.
The tensions in the markets have led to a twofold government response.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero announced new adjustment measures, ranging from tax cuts for SMEs, regulation of private employment agencies or the abolition of the 426 euro unemployment benefit without professional contribution to the privatisation of 49% of AENA, the management of Barajas and El Prat airports and 30% of the State Lotteries.
On the other hand, Vice-President Elena Salgado, with the support of former President Felipe González, joined in criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel for her responsibility in unleashing the current crisis.
How are these movements to be interpreted?
It should be noted that Merkel's position is not a mistake in her communication policy.
On the contrary, it is another constraint on the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And here Germany has a radically new vision of what its future must be, which clashes with the old traditions of most of its partners.
In the face of European resistance, Germany is beginning to speculate on three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first is a strong euro, with Austria, Holland and other countries, and the south leaving the eurozone.
The second is the recovery of the Mark, even if now it seems like science fiction, with a very favorable opinion, almost 50% of the population.
Thirdly, a new design of the euro, in line with German proposals for greater macroeconomic control, budgetary rigor, fines for countries that break them, possible suspensions of payments for one of them and extension to the private sector of the costs of potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and has been for a long time, so now there is no room for excuses.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission were stimulating deficits, the German government invented a constitutional reform to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of a divergence between what Germany thought should be done (fiscal rigor and fiscal stability plans) and what its European partners, including France, were doing.
The second blow to the Central European country was when Merkel had difficulty extending the decision to bail out Greece.
Since then it has been the subject of fierce criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public and press opinion were against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, towards the end of October, Merkel again expressed a clear position, calling for reform of the Union's Treaties to enable a country to be rescued and at the same time oblige private lenders to bear part of the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, because it precipitated the Irish crisis and the rest.
But his proposal, albeit a little watered down, was approved and in the months ahead we should see the process of reforming the Union to make these measures possible from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
And it tells us all that, even if we now have to take measures with which we may not agree too much, from that date the old way of working of the euro would be over.
2013 will mean the birth of a new currency area, in which countries that break the rules will be severely punished, they may be forced to cease payments and, in that case, the private sector will also bear some of the costs.
Germany is signalling that we must pursue a severe growth path with high saving and investment rates, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness and positive external balances.
An alternative based on debt and construction, with huge gaps in the balance of payments, such as the one that presided over Spanish growth in the boom years, will simply not be tolerated.
The stakes are clear.
And it would be wrong not to hear it.
It is not just a question of bringing the government deficit back to 3% in 2013.
What we're being asked to do is much harder.
