Sports and law-abiding fraud
The similar ruses of Alonso and Ramos against Ajax demonstrate ingenuity but not the will to escape a penalty.
The expulsion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) during the November 23 match against Ajax in the Champions League has cast a lot of ink on the unsportsmanlike nature of such behaviour and whether the two players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is known, a few minutes before the end of the match (which their team was already clearly winning), both players deliberately wasted time when they made mistakes to determine the referee to show them the second yellow card.
Thus, and as Real Madrid will end up leading their group, both players will complete the regulatory penalty during the next game of the first leg against Auxerre and can go through to the next round without cards.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee sanctioned the team's coach, José Mourinho, with two games and various sums of money to the players involved.
Provoking a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, if not quite common in the world of football.
It's so widespread that it's part of the ethos, the unwritten but followed rules of the sport.
Part of the debate in the case is due to the fact that it involved a team from the Real Madrid entity (which in its anthem displays nobility and honor and which in the past has fined its players for similar acts) and the dramatization, it seems, orchestrated by Mourinho, which adds another episode to his long history of being a provocative and histrionic coach.
In any case, the debate asks whether this type of behaviour not expressly prohibited by the regulations is contrary to the principles of sport, that is, whether these actions are a fraud; because, in fact, they are actions which respect the rules of the sport, but seem to elude their meaning.
The question is what kind of damage they do to the spirit of sport.
One of the goods that comprises the spirit of sport is the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect which has not been endangered by these actions, that is, there has been no violent play.
Another of these goods referred to with fair play is to prevent the offending team from taking unfair advantage of the opposing team, which is not the case either.
However, the paradoxical fact of the action of the Real Madrid players is that they do not settle for what is normally characterized as cheating or fraud of the law, because their violation of the rules was not done in secret to try to avoid the penalty, but their action precisely tried to be as obvious as possible to receive the penalty from the referee.
They waited and they accepted the punishment.
Another issue is the type of advantage that offenders get from the intentional wrongs examined.
It seems necessary to note here that one does not put one's opponent at a disadvantage and one does not gain an advantage in the same match either, because obviously the result of the action is to leave one's own team with fewer players.
And it's not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club couldn't count on these players.
The advantage is, of course, that the players will start the next phase of the Champions League without any cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with some degree of indeterminacy, because the team could be eliminated suddenly and apart from that, with this action the players complete a penalty match and move on to the second round of cards, in which the suspension due to accumulation of cards occurs with one less than in the first round.
So, moving up the ladder, it's not so clear that that's an advantage.
In the end, these actions are not contrary to the spirit of sport, which nevertheless includes the making of strategic decisions that promote profit as much as the rules allow.
In our case, the players did not act to avoid the penalty (this would be a clear case of fraud), but they chose the moment when they submitted to it.
They made a strategic decision without dodging or avoiding the penalty.
Although the line between genius and legal fraud is blurred, on this occasion I think we had a clear case of genius.
The controversy, I think, arises because of two factors: because there were two self-expulsions and because of the way the principal was transmitted to provoke them.
The damage to the principles of sport caused by these actions is not so much ethical as aesthetic.
