Romano chasing his first title
Rubén Omar Romano lost three finals, he had ups and downs in his career, but he made it to the deciding series three times.
With Santos Laguna and Monterrey in the final, there are also two different styles facing off, scored by their technicians, who find a marked contrast between them in the results.
Rubén Omar Romano has lost three finals, he's had ups and downs in his career, but he's managed to reach the deciding series three times, even though so far he hasn't put in the effort and that's why this opportunity is very special for him.
Argentina ended up consolating themselves with the runner-up medal, they stayed one step behind the winners and curiously with the same team they played consecutive finals.
The Santista strategist reached his first final as a coach in the 2002 Opening Tournament, when he held the reins of Morelia with which he lost with an overall result of 4-2 against Toluca; later, in the 2003 Closing he also reached the decisive duel and lost again with the overall result of 3-1 and this was precisely against Rayados.
With Santos Laguna already, in the 2010 Bicentennial Tournament, again against the Diablos, Rubén suffered another setback, as his team made a 2-2 draw against the Choriceros after 210 minutes of play, but in the penalty shoot-out he got a 3-1 lead with two chances to get the title and finally three of his players missed by 11 yards and he suffered the jump to the result of 4-3.
Rubén lost two finals with the Diablos Rojos and one with Monterrey, his rival in the tournament, so he does not want to suffer the same fate, he tries to break free from the curse to celebrate a title for the first time, even though he claims that for him the institution is more important.
"I want to be champion, I don't want to break any statistics, this is for a club, not for a passion that I have and therefore I will get the title, but what I mentioned before is more important", commented the helmsman when asked what his weak points would be in the finals.
He remembers a lot of the last final, from which he says he learned a lot, "the only lesson we can take is that until the referee whistles the final, we can't celebrate, we are prepared in the line, the players too, because last time, with two penalties to shoot we were already ready to run and I think this is a lesson, before the end of the game we can't celebrate".
He knows that this series could be decided by penalties, which he is not worried about, because he trusts his players: "We never try to get to the penalty shootout, we try to finish in the regular time, but sometimes we have to prepare, the previous tournament we were prepared, unfortunately fate did not turn us around, sometimes it is the emotions or the anxiety of holding the title in our hands, it escaped us, it served us as a lesson for this final and we hope that we do not get into this situation again".
Romano now has the opportunity to step away from being a second-champion technician and taste for the first time the glory that titles bring.
The European Union changes the rules for obtaining visas
People should go to the Visa Applicant Service Centre before their interview in the Consular Section; the cost and waiting time will be reduced.
As of January 10, 2011, the visa processing procedure at the U.S. Embassy and Consulate will change.
With the new procedure, most applicants will have to report to the Visa Applicants Service Centre (ASC) before their interview in the Consular Section.
The AAC staff will take the applicant's biometric information, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section before the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for applicants, including the following:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, there will be no need to pay one payment for an appointment, another for processing the visa and another for the mail service to deliver the document.
The applicant will make a one-off payment covering all three services.
The current fee will remain the same: $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for an application visa (including temporary workers' visas) and $390 for business and investor visas.
Persons wishing to renew their visas will not have to appear for an interview with the Consular Representative, they will only appear at the nearest ASC where they will present their documents and have their fingerprints taken.
Because biometric information will be taken at the CSA, applicants who wish to make a second appointment to be interviewed at the Consular Section will be there for less time than before.
Similarly, visa applicants at the Consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of $26 (U.S.).
For more information on the new visa application procedure, please visit the following page: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/bulletins/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
NASA to announce discovery of alien life
The U.S. space agency has quoted the press to announce a discovery tomorrow that will have an impact on the search for living things in space.
The National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) of the United States will announce tomorrow, Thursday, an astrobiological discovery that could prove the theory of the existence of extraterrestrial life.
The discovery will be presented at a press conference tomorrow, Thursday, at 1:00 p.m. at NASA headquarters in Washington to experts in astrobiology, the science that studies the origin, evolution, distribution and future of life in the universe.
When quoting the press, NASA assured that it would present the results that would have an impact on the search for extraterrestrial life", which has prompted speculation from experts in other countries.
The discovery could demonstrate the theory that there are creatures similar to us in hostile environments that were previously thought uninhabitable and could put on the table the possibility of becoming intelligent beings like humans if their living conditions are improved.
It seems to be a microbe found at the bottom of Mono Lake in Yosemite National Park, California, which lives in an environment that was thought to be too toxic for any life form because the lake is rich in arsenic.
Either way, the creature uses arsenic as a way of life, and this ability leads us to think that similar life could exist on other planets that don't have our volunteer atmosphere.
According to astrobiologists, the fact that these organisms use arsenic in their metabolism proves that "there is another form of life, a second form of life, different from the one we know".
The space agency will announce the true extent of the findings at a press conference tomorrow, Thursday.
The conference will include geobiologist Pamela Conrad, who studies the possibility of life on Mars, and biologist Steven Benner, one of the scientists who studies Titan (Saturn's largest satellite), with the prospect that its chemistry is similar to Earth's.
The PRD, PT, Convergencia and Patrón are opposing
With reforms to the Organic Act of Congress, the arrival of 'bipartisanship' is being made possible, it is said.
The 60th had just taken over when an opposition bloc emerged in Congress led by the members of the PRD, PT, Convergencia and Jesús Manuel Patrón Montalvo, who declared himself independent and all four questioned one thing: the arrival of 'bipartism' in the Chambers.
Before the start of the 60th Parliament, Felipe Manzanarez Rodríguez of Convergencia, Ezequiel Reynoso Esparza of PT, Javier Corvera Quevedo of PRD and Patrón Montalvo were all against the reform of the Organic Law, because it excluded them from the legislative process.
With this reform, they reiterated, we are starting bipartisanship because now there are two people, from the same number of parties, controlling Congress.
These four members, alongside Gloria Margarita Santos Aguilar, PRD coordinator, were the only ones to vote against the Board chaired by PANist Salvador López Brito and Luis Antonio Cárdenas Fonseca, as vice-president.
Corvera Quevedo mentioned that these reforms constitute the political marginalisation of the PRI and PAN in an institutional way.
He mentioned that in the following days they would talk to the PAN and PRI representatives to change the pattern based on political will and if they do not have it, they will be enslaved by both parties again and thus the opposition coalition will end.
"So far (the opposition coalition) has come, that's what I'm looking at, because we're excluded from any decision, they don't even have the political deference to consider the opinion of the rest".
Felipe Manzanarez Rodríguez, from Convergencia mentioned that with PRD, PT and Patrón there are coincidences and that is why they form a plural group.
He said that the Congress, once monopolistic, cannot be allowed to become "duopolistic".
"It is not in the spirit of law reform that there should be a perpetual bipartisanship in Congress".
To begin with, this group starts with 5 lawmakers and they are now talking to other colleagues to get more, said Convergent.
Ezequiel Reynoso Esparza, from PT, explained that now the Congress has become a 'booty' between the two, referring to PAN and PRI.
"Before there was only one party, now they divide it into two".
Patrón Montalvo asked that the Member's personality be respected and that he be given a seat at the negotiating table.
"They are not leaving by cupola agreements out to 5 who will probably be 9 deputies, now at the five we are seen, separated into different fractions, we have decided to unite to seek a place at the negotiating table, that is the problem, that in the reform they have made, that they have decided, we are out and we do not agree with that reform".
$200 million more for "the supplier"
The city of Mazatlan is paying another check to the owner of the electrical equipment company in question.
Another check for about 200 thousand pesos in favor of Lorena Guadalupe Camacho Palazuelos was issued by the City Hall.
With this, the amount paid this second half to the owner of the electrical equipment company amounts to 1 million 200 thousand pesos.
According to the Municipality's transparency page, the latest check, number 9258447, was issued on November 16 for the amount of 200 thousand 144.56 pesos, in the concept of "liquidation of suppliers' accounts".
Treasurer Luis Miguel López Moreno had said that the municipality would pay additional amounts to this supplier, which was observed by the State Audit Office to sell at a higher price.
What is not reported is the total debt and, therefore, cheque books will still be issued in favour of Camacho Palazuelos.
"We bought nothing, we just paid him what we owe him, like the rest of the suppliers", he said in an interview.
The last cheques "reappeared" in the last quarter of the year: on 24 September, two on 15 October, 19 October, 29 October and the last on 16 November.
Although the supplier has not yet published in the Official State Gazette, as provided for in the Act when an undertaking is interviewed by ASE, to prevent other governments from using its services, the Treasurer has assured that they have not used its services again.
After all this, on July 25, Noroeste published a review of the checks that the City issued to its suppliers, revealing that between March 2008 and July 2010, during the three-year term of Mayor Jorge Abel López Sánchez, the Municipality paid Camacho Palazuelos more than 10 million pesos, through 42 checks.
He also made transactions with Jumapam, cashing checks worth over 3 million pesos.
Tourist sites must be cleaned
The tourism entrepreneurs regret the accident of the foreign tourist because of the poor conditions at the Sánchez Taboada roundabout in Mazatlán.
After a foreign tourist fell into a ditch at the Sánchez Taboada roundabout, the tourism sector in Mazatlán asked the authorities to pay attention to areas and sites that are in poor condition and project a bad image of the port.
Salvador Barraza Rubio, president of the Zona Dorada Merchants Association, said they have repeatedly asked for the destination's image to be taken care of and that new activities should replace the ones that tourists find bad.
He said the poor condition of the streets and sidewalks has affected as tourists come to walk around and they see the mess and avoid the nearby shops.
"Politicians don't know what it means to close a business one day and they don't know the fortune you lose, elsewhere they wouldn't have done the work for so long and without proper planning".
Hotel owner José Ramón Manguart Sánchez said the tourist's fall exposed the lack of prevention and maintenance by the City Hall.
"The mayor will have to take responsibility and prevent this from happening again, how to do it, so through a preventive maintenance and not just do the corrective", he said.
"We want to enjoy a clean city, because not only because it is a tourist area we have to maintain it, but as residents who deserve a clean place to live and the City Council has to change its strategy to maintain the city well".
There are other sites that are neglected and incomplete, he said, such as Escudo and Venadito de Mazatlán.
"Today, because tourists come, it doesn't just depend on promotion, there has to be a good product, a city that has cleanliness in its beaches, boulevards, permanent maintenance of tourist attractions", he said.
"They have not been given the attention they deserve and this kind of thing highlights something that is well known to all, maintenance is necessary".
Raúl Llera Martínez, Undersecretary for Tourism Promotion, said that the recovery of Mazatlán's tourist sites is urgent, as they are not used properly and project a bad image.
He spoke of a series of places that must be put in line with the municipality and be a priority to have the city up to date, clean, orderly and attractive because it has a tourist vocation.
"Fortunately Mazatlán has many historical and cultural sites and places that we should first order, clean and put online to make them attractive so that we can add them to the inventory we have to promote this destination".
IP calls for results in Congress
Eduardo Dávalos, president of CCE, proposed that the deputies take on the great responsibility of being an example for a better Sinaloa because of the various provocations it faces.
The business sector in Mazatlán is calling for a worthy working legislature free of agreements between the parties and the government executive, as Sinaloa is in convulsion and faces major problems.
Yesterday the 60th legislature was installed, made up of seven political forces, 19 PRI deputies, 13 PAN deputies, three New Alliance deputies, two PRD deputies, one PT deputies, one Convergencia deputies and one PVEM deputies, a total of 40 people's representatives.
The list of expectations that the new members of the Government Congress have is a clean and committed management with society and the different sectors that need responsible legislative work and that the same patterns of partisan spirit or paternalism are not repeated.
Eduardo Dávalos, president of CCE, proposed that the deputies take on the great responsibility of being an example for a better Sinaloa because of the various provocations it faces.
"We hope that the MPs will actually exercise their right, free from party agreements because the custom is that they make pacts to protect their own interests and they turn into a carnival masquerade of governors and parliamentary group leaders".
I therefore ask them to certify their commitment to building the necessary bridges that will allow the present Government to move forward.
"We will ensure that they do a dignified job and above all engaged with society and sectors because the people of Sinaloa gave them their vote of confidence in the last elections.
José Ramón Manguart Sánchez, president of the Tres Islas Hotel Association, said that one of the major challenges facing the 40 popular representatives is to push and add strength to the economic growth of the state, as the economic situation is now very complicated.
"The most important thing is that they drive economic growth, that they generate incentives for investment and infrastructure and that in a way will stimulate job creation".
On tourism, he asked that the new legislators give it the importance it has in the government budget to consolidate the Government Tourism Secretariat.
"I understand that it is the second Secretariat of State with a smaller budget and it is incongruous as an important economic activity and generates foreign exchange and investment and competes directly with the agro-industry".
Apart from the fact that we need to allocate resources to detonator tourism projects that help provide security to the state and update the Alcohol Act that previous legislatures failed to resolve.
We're looking for a wizard king.
Among other toys, the children of the Coronado Valenzuela family want dolls, cars and bicycles.
For their parents, the next day of the Magi will be difficult to fulfill their dreams, because their home is made up of no more than 12 people and a goat.
However, Adelaida, Isabel, Jesús, José Alfredo, María Guadalupe, Isaías, José Juan, and Miguel never lose hope that Melchior, Balthazar, and Gaspard will bring them the toys and clothes they so desperately desire.
The family lives in a modest house in Colonia Salvador Allende and they live day to day because their father does not have a stable job.
"Sometimes it is very difficult for us, because my husband has no job, but we sell tangerines and potatoes...and in the afternoon I go out with the 'plebes' to sell on the street", says Cayetana Valenzuela Andrade, the mother of the children.
Adelaida, 4, wants a doll or a bicycle, and her sister Isabel, 3, wants a Barbie doll.
Ten-year-old José Alfredo has long wanted a monster truck, and eight-month-old Jesús Cayetana suggests a year's worth of clothes.
"He (José Alfredo) said, 'I'd like to have this monster,' but I said, 'We'll see, son,' because it was very expensive", recalls Cayetana sadly.
For older children, who were in school, clothes and shoes would be ideal.
María Guadalupe, 11, wears a size 12 shoe; Isaías, 10, wears a size 10, and Miguel, 8, wears a size 8.
José Juan, 14, needs a pair of sneakers, so a pair of size five and a half or six would be a big help.
If you want to help make the dream of the Coronado Valenzuela family's children a reality you can join the "We're Looking for a Magician King" campaign by donating a toy or money to the Northwest Reception.
14 suspected drug traffickers arrested
Around ten searches were carried out in Estrie on Wednesday as part of the dismantling of a network of cannabis production and sale.
Fourteen people have been arrested and will face various charges.
The searches took place in Sherbrooke, Orford and Stoke, mostly in places where drugs were allegedly produced.
"About 750 cannabis plants, four kilograms of hashish, money and equipment used for production were seized", said Louis-Philippe Ruel, a spokesman for the Sûreté du Québec.
In all, 11 men and three women were arrested, including the two alleged leaders of the network, two men from Sherbrooke.
Those arrested were to appear at the Sherbrooke Courthouse within hours of their arrest.
They could face charges of cannabis production, possession with intent to traffic, conspiracy and theft of services, among others.
These searches were the result of a lengthy investigation that lasted almost a year.
"It was information from the public that allowed us to make these arrests", Ruel said.
Some 70 police officers from the regional investigation unit of the Estre de la Sûreté du Québec, the Sherbrooke Police Service and the Memphremagog Police Regiment took part in the police operation.
The illegal migration will continue without problems
The Conservative bill, which the government says should address the problem of boats carrying illegal migrants, is clearly going to be defeated after the three opposition parties said on Wednesday they could not support it.
"I rely heavily on the Charter".
"I stand with a party that has created the granite under your feet", said Liberal leader Michael Ignatieff, as he was surrounded by lawmakers after the weekly caucus meeting.
The Liberals claim that the bill as proposed, which would allow for up to one year of detention of anyone from a ship identified as carrying illegal immigrants, would violate the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms.
The leader of the Bloc Québécois, Gilles Duceppe, also indicated that he could not support the bill, because it was targeting the wrong target.
"We are against it and it seems that all the opposition parties are against it, so we will see what the government does", said Duceppe.
NDP immigration critic Olivia Chow has dismissed criticism that her party is not strong enough on illegal immigrants.
"The NDP agrees that we should take action against smugglers and we are doing that through another bill, Bill C-35", said Ms Chow.
"We do not support the Conservative bill because it targets refugees and imprisons children for at least a year", Ms Chow said.
Immigration Minister Jason Kenney accused opposition parties of playing politics and ignoring the will of Canadians.
"Canadians are telling MPs in droves that they will not tolerate this kind of illegal migration, these criminal operations that target Canada and treat the country like a doormat".
"They expect Canada to take firm action", Minister Kenney said.
The government has not announced a vote of confidence in its bill, which could have led to elections in the country if it was rejected.
A Conservative told the QMI Agency, however, that the government would call for a vote so that each MP who opposes it would then explain himself to his constituents.
The new unity is not unanimous
Despite the announcement of the possible creation of a permanent unit to fight corruption and collusion by Jean Charest, many observers continue to call for the creation of a public inquiry commission into the matter.
Public Safety Minister Robert Dutil says the idea is not new: Quebec reportedly consulted the New York Department of Investigation about it as early as January.
The Metropolis has had a permanent corruption unit since 1870.
Yet Tuesday's announcement surprised many.
It must be said that at a meeting of the Permanent Council on the Police Services of Quebec on 29 October last, this measure was never discussed despite the presence of Robert Dutil.
It was only fitting that the PQ critic of public safety, Stéphane Bergeron, called the announcement "a rabbit out of a hat" and "a tinkered solution in the corner of a table".
Minister Dutil responded to those who fear that political power will have too much influence on possible future unity.
"You'll see the result when we announce it", he merely said.
"We're aware of that problem".
For the president of the CSQ, Réjean Parent, nothing can replace the establishment of a public inquiry.
"The more Mr Charest insists on not wanting to create this commission of inquiry, the more people think like you and me that he has something to hide", he explains.
"The only way to have a commission of inquiry is for Jean Charest to resign", says Yves Boisvert, professor of ethics and governance at the National School of Public Administration.
To break this deadlock, he therefore suggests that Quebec give a special mandate to the Auditor General to investigate collusion and corruption.
'We must be able to extend the mandate of the Auditor-General,' he said.
He also believes that Quebec could give the auditor the same powers as a commissioner, thus allowing him to compel people to testify.
The creation of a permanent squad is not the only project in the cartons of the Charest government.
Quebec would also ask Ottawa to amend the Criminal Code to make it more appropriate for this type of crime.
This request is said to have come from the prosecutor of the operation Marteau, who informed the Minister of Justice Jean-Marc Fournier that the case law is not explicit in this kind of investigation.
Federal Minister for Public Safety Vic Toews confirmed that his Justice Minister colleague Rob Nicholson is currently working on some amendments to the case.
In the spring 2001 operation, which targeted motorcycle gangs, 131 people were arrested, even though the Criminal Code was not adapted.
Ottawa later passed the Gangsterism Act.
Rivers under strict surveillance
Several streams remain under close surveillance due to heavy rainfall that has fallen in several parts of the province since Tuesday.
A landslide occurred Wednesday afternoon in Shawinigan, Mauritius.
Two homes were evacuated as a precaution.
In the evening, another landslide is said to have occurred in Saint-Lin-Laurentides, Lanaudière.
A road has sunk.
From Tuesday to Wednesday evening, heavy rain fell in several areas, with 40 to 70 millimeters of rain falling.
An additional 20 to 40 millimeters of rain were expected by Thursday evening, depending on the region.
The areas north of the river and in the Outaouais Valley were the most affected.
They could receive up to 100 millimeters of rain in total.
In addition to the snow melting already in some areas, there is concern that several rivers may overflow.
Flood warnings were issued Wednesday evening by the Civil Security of Quebec for the Ouareau and Achigan rivers in Lanaudière.
The rivers to the north, at Saint-Jérôme, in the Laurentians, and the Château, in Lotbinière, were subject to flood watches and were kept under surveillance.
In the Lanaudière region, heavy rainfall caused some lakes to overflow, including St. Julienne, St. Marceline-de-Kildare and Rawdon.
In St. Calyx, a temporary bridge was washed away by heavy rains.
Ten homes had to be evacuated as a precautionary measure.
In Ottawa, overflow of some lakes has led to the closure of several roads, notably in the municipality of Mansfield-et-Pontefract.
The Civil Security remains on alert and is closely monitoring the situation, said Annik Bouchard, security adviser.
The Quebec Flood Prediction Centre issued flood warnings for several rivers on Wednesday, including Maskinongé, L'Assomption, Ouareau, Achigan, Batiscan and du Loup.
Dupont partly to blame
Quebec radio host Stéphane Dupont has suffered a partial setback before the Canadian Broadcasting Standards Council (CCNR) for controversial remarks about welfare and Haitians as well as his on-air slur.
The CCNR found that Dupont and his team at CHOI 98.1 FM were entitled to express their opinions, but that some of the comments contained "incorrect information about social assistance, unduly negative portrayals of Haitians and rude language that is not appropriate for daytime broadcasts".
The Council also concluded that a discussion on suicide, including the broadcasting of the names of two people who had committed suicide, did not violate broadcasting codes.
The CCNR had received several complaints about comments made during programmes broadcast between 2008 and 2010.
The first decision was made following a complaint from the Front commun des personnes assistées sociales du Québec.
The group complained that the amounts quoted in the programme were inaccurate.
The presenters should present solid information rather than misleading information.
In the case of suicide, the host Stéphane Dupont had said that suicide was a cowardly act.
The majority of the Committee members concluded that the message was that suicide should not be viewed as a solution to life's problems.
"The majority of the Committee considers that the contested episodes of 'Dupont le Midi' have addressed a sensitive subject in a fair and appropriate manner".
So no blame was placed on him.
The latest case concerned statements made after the earthquake in Haiti.
Stéphane Dupont and Jean-René Dufort had then engaged in a face-to-face media confrontation that had aroused much reaction.
The host of CHOI said he had not made any donations to help Haitians because it was not known for sure that the needy people would actually receive the money.
The Committee believes that these comments were not abusive but that their cumulative effect is an unduly negative representation of Haitians.
"I've already served my three-day suspension on that".
"My record has been blank for a year and a half", said the host.
In all its decisions, the Committee condemns the use of vulgar language.
In each case, CHOI-FM cooperated "beyond its obligation".
The consequences for the station are minimal, as it will have to announce these decisions once every three days during peak hours.
A kung fu king in Montreal
Montreal native Nacereddine Zemmal has a very special career.
The athlete who excels in sanda (kung fu "full contact"), kickboxing, and Thai boxing climbs tatami mats and rings around the world in search of new challenges.
"I started practicing martial arts like kung fu and kickboxing 12 years ago in Algeria", said Zemmal, who moved to the capital in 2008 to train as a professional.
"For me, I look for fights everywhere, since for those who don't like the floor play of mixed martial arts, competitions are rare in North America".
Recently, the UPS security guard and employee delivered the bad news to his rivals by winning two gold medals at the World Karate and Kickboxing Association (WKA) Amateur World Championships, held October 23-30, in Edinburgh, Scotland.
"I won the full contact kickboxing and Thai boxing categories", he explained.
"I'm currently preparing to go to China for the World Cup of San Shou".
"Fighters who finished in the top four at the last world championships in each category were invited".
"I won bronze in 2009 in Toronto".
"In 2005, in Vietnam, I finished eighth".
"In 2007, in China, I finished fifth, while in Toronto in 2009, I finished third", he added.
"The interesting thing is that I've improved in every competition".
"At this rate, I'll be first this time or next year!"
San shou or sanda is a martial art originating in China where punching and kicking, as well as throwing on the ground, are allowed.
Duels were originally held on a platform and less often in a ring.
The most famous boxer to emerge from this form of combat is Vietnamese-American Cung Le, well-known in the martial arts world.
If Nacer Zemmal has to remember only one event in his career, he will surely answer by attending the super tournament "King of Sanda", the Kung Fu Super Bowl.
"This is the most important and prestigious competition in China", said the friendly young man.
"It's a bit like the Lumpinee Stadium (the largest stadium in Thailand)".
"It was a great experience".
Zemmal won his first fight, in the semi-finals of his category (80 kg), before losing in the final.
"The man who beat me was a real pro", he analyzed.
"There are four fighters per category (80kg, 85kg, 90kg and 90kg)".
"The winners of the semi-finals will face each other in the final of their respective categories".
"Then the winners of each category face off to crown a single champion, the kung fu king".
450 million in contracts without tenders
Hydro-Québec has voluntarily awarded $450 million in contracts to engineering firms for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert hydroelectric project.
At the heart of this avalanche of more than 100 contracts was a consortium of BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor, which won the largest, the project management contract, for a sum of $295 million without a tender.
This consortium, called Énergie gérance, was formed in 2004 when Hydro-Québec decided to entrust the private sector with the management of this important $5 billion hydroelectric project.
In early 2005, the energy management consortium won the lucrative contract without a public tender.
The Parti Québécois considers that the use of consortia of undertakings poses a serious ethical problem which may eliminate competition and cause prices to rise.
"It's the new way to collusion and kill competition".
"That is to say, people, instead of doing it in secret, now do it openly", said yesterday the PQ MP Sylvain Simard at a press conference.
Earlier in the morning, Mr Simard raised the issue in the National Assembly because he said he could hardly see how the public interest could be served in this way.
The Minister of Natural Resources, Nathalie Normandeau, responded this afternoon, vigorously denying that there was collusion for this contract.
"I'm starting to have my journey", she said, claiming that the PQ had been "dishonest" and "lacking in rigor".
She said it would be the least of the things that the PQ should apologize.
The consortium formula is a common practice throughout the world.
It is usually a time-limited alliance that allows two or more companies to pool their respective expertise to respond to a call for tender for a complex project.
The Eastmain project is of a high level of complexity given the scale of the work.
The construction is under way and is scheduled to last until 2012.
However, the contract was awarded without the competition being involved; negotiation took place.
The consortium formula is no longer an exception in Quebec, even for relatively simple projects.
As Le Devoir revealed last week, the consortium formula in the engineering consultancy sector is being investigated by the government.
A quick glance at the Quebec business register shows that there are over 200 consortia, some of which appear to be permanent.
Dessau thus works in partnership with most of its main competitors, including CIMA+, Génivar, SNC-Lavalin and others such as Roche and Tecsult.
Each combination, and there are dozens of them, leads to one and the same legal entity, Dessau.
Regarding the Energy Management Consortium, Minister Normandeau stressed that "the James Bay region responds to particular labour dynamics and Hydro-Québec has responded to them in a particular way since the 1970s".
The big boss of the Eastmain project, Real Laporte of the James Bay Energy Company (SEBJ), gave an explanation that made eyebrows that the project management contract was given on a voluntary basis.
"If you go to the auction and there are few bidders, your prices will be higher".
"You have two choices: either you take the people in that market and you say, 'We're going to negotiate a satisfactory deal at a good price.'"
"But the idea is that it is not the price that is important, it is the skill of the people", Laporte said.
This contract awarded to the consortium Énergie gérance is one of a long list of contracts worth more than $50,000 won by the Parti Québécois.
The contracts were awarded by Hydro-Québec or SEBJ for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert project.
After verification, Le Devoir counted 109 engineering consultancy contracts awarded between 2002 and March 2010 to firms or their subsidiaries, including soil laboratories.
SNC-Lavalin won 22 contracts, Génivar won 16, Tecsult 14 and Dessau 10, not including its participation in Énergie gérance.
All the contracts have been negotiated.
They total $449,783,344, including the $295,131,564 contract to Managed Energy.
Sylvain Simard suggested that the four firms that make up the consortium (BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor) are "well known to the Liberal Party of Quebec".
