The UN yesterday proposed in Cancun a plan to upgrade domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries to achieve a reduction in greenhouse gases (GHG) that is almost one third of the additional reduction needed to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan follows on from the major concrete projects that the UN hopes to have adopted in Cancun to compensate for the absence of binding reduction commitments by the industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs that still dominate 50 to 70 percent of the market were replaced by fluorescent bulbs or, better, by light-emitting diode (LED) bulbs, most of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GHG emitted on the planet to light humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is equivalent to 70% of the global car fleet's emissions.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitter countries such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that are expected to bring global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But we need to subtract another 5 Gt from this balance to stabilise the rise in the climate to 2 degrees Celsius by 2020 to prevent it from getting out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95 percent of the energy is dissipated as heat and the remaining 5 percent is produced as light.
With fluorescent light bulbs, the energy consumption is reduced by 75%, and with the new LED light bulbs, the energy requirement is reduced by half.
Fluoridation bulbs last on average between 6,000 and 10,000 hours.
New LED bulbs, such as those launched this week by the manufacturer Philips - which was also involved in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and use 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, which gives an idea of the possible savings with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
These new bulbs can also work with rheostats and emit very little heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations about fluorescent bulbs, since they contain mercury and must be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless manufacturers have guidelines in place.
But the report says that the world's main source of mercury emissions is not the fluorescent bulb, but rather coal-fired power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce electricity wasted in incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury a year.
The report details the gains each country would make from this international programme.
