Vengeful hackers and spies on the move
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it is an apparent scandal, a scandal which only appears as a scandal in the face of the hypocrisy which governs relations between States, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it heralds profound changes at the international level, and foreshadows a future dominated by regression.
But let's proceed in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation that every file that is created by a secret service (of any nation) is made up exclusively of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" US revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits are just reports that have been in any newspaper for months (except the ones Berlusconi owns), and Gaddafi's ominously caricatural profile has long been the stuff of cabaret sketches.
The rule that secret files must be composed only of new ones that are already known is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not just in this century.
If you go to a bookstore devoted to esoteric literature, you will find that each book - on the Grail, the Rennes-le-Château mystery, the Templars, or the Rose-Cross - repeats exactly what was already written in the earlier books.
Not only is the author of occult texts averse to new research (or uncertain where to look for information about the nonexistent), but those who practice occultism believe only in what they already know, which confirms what they have already learned.
That's the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
Same with the classified files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or limited-minded) is the head of the secret service (otherwise he could be, I don't know, editor at Liberation), who only holds true what he admits.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the US Embassy in Rome was sending to the State Department was the same as the one that Newsweek had published the week before.
So why have the revelations about these files been such a buzz?
On the one hand, they say what any educated person already knows, namely that embassies, at least since the end of World War II, and since heads of state can telephone or fly to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, except for a few small representative exercises, have become spy centers.
Any investigative film-goer knows this very well, and it is only through hypocrisy that people pretend not to know.
However, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and serves to cast a bad light on American diplomacy.
Second, the idea that any hacker could capture the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a major blow to the prestige of the State Department.
The scandal therefore puts the victims in crisis rather than the "executioners".
But let's get to the bottom of what happened.
Back in Orwell's day, you could think of all power as a Big Brother controlling every move of his subjects.
Orwellian prophecy had completely come true since, by being able to control every move through the phone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway taken and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the eye of power.
But when you show, as is happening now, that even the crypt of power's secrets cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be one-way and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - elected as the citizen's avenger - can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that can no longer keep its own secrets stand?
It is true, Georg Simmel said, that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that anything about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed an empty secret, because it is in the public domain; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks did, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets means to take away all her power.
WikiLeaks did no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but it did too much harm to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound inflicted on a very powerful power?
It is obvious that in the future, states will no longer be able to put any confidential information online - it would be like posting it on a street corner poster.
But it is just as obvious that with today's technology, it is futile to hope to have confidential telephone conversations.
Nothing easier than finding out if and when a head of state flew and contacted a colleague.
How will private and private relations be maintained in the future?
I know that my prediction is science fiction and therefore romantic, but I am forced to imagine government agents moving discreetly in stagecoaches on uncontrollable routes, carrying only memorized messages or, at best, hiding the rare information written on the heel of a shoe.
The information will be kept in single copies in locked drawers: after all, the Watergate spy attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I have had the opportunity to write that technology is now moving forward in a crab-like fashion, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet has brought back wired telegraph.
Whereas video (analog) cassettes had allowed film researchers to explore a film step by step, going back and forth and discovering all the secrets of editing, now CDs (digital) only allow for skipping from chapter to chapter, i.e. by macroportions.
With high-speed trains, you can travel from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, which includes the trip, it takes three and a half hours.
It is not surprising, then, that politics and communications technology have become like chariots on horses.
One last thing.
In the past, the press tried to understand what was going on in the secret embassies.
Now it's the embassies that ask the press for confidential information.
Climate: How France is faking its funding promises
One year after the Copenhagen Accord, it is time to review the implementation of promises of fast-start financing by developed countries.
And the big French rigging is revealed.
In the Copenhagen Accord, developed countries pledged $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has pledged 7.2 billion euros over three years and France 1.26 billion euros (or 420 million a year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU played the game to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start financing: report detailing the action of its Member States, press conference, large side event, distribution of brochures...
The transparency operation is appreciated and appreciated for its worth: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with the same level of accuracy.
The EU says it has committed €2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to meet its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look in detail, things get more complicated.
This money must, according to the Copenhagen agreement, be 'new and additional' to ensure that additional effort is made without detriment to official development aid.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what is meant by "new and additional".
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
Today, each person chooses the reference that suits him best.
The European Commission, for example, has taken 2009 as the reference year: international financing is maintained, and it adds 150 million over three years under fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks in terms of year or level of ODA.
On the other hand, France considers that the funding for 'all new projects' in 2010 is 'new and additional'.
In other words, there is no reference to expenditure in previous years or to the overall level of ODA.
In practice, the total amount of French aid to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), and it claims to be complying with its commitment to 'new and additional' financing.
Another crucial factor is the distribution of donations and loans.
Again, there is no rule and each person chooses his own calculation method.
Some, such as France, consider that one euro lent is equal to one euro given.
Of course, this is hardly justifiable: the effort is not comparable.
While the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to the reduction of emissions that rely on more efficient technologies), it is misleading to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is given.
But France has no reason to be concerned with such reasoning: it 'fulfils' its €420 million commitment by making 91.5% loans (€389.8 million) and 8.5% donations (€36.1 million) - see the EU document to check for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union to make such a massive use of the loan.
Germany requires 46% of the funds, while Denmark, the Netherlands and Slovakia (among others) meet their commitments with 100% of the funds.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union puts in €1 to meet its commitment, France puts in only 10 cents and considers the effort to be comparable.
Nice trick of the cross.
In short, in its fast start financing, France is committing a double fraud: on the one hand, on the evolution of the action over time and, on the other, on the reality of the financial effort.
By spending only €36.1 million, it succeeds in making it appear that it is spending €420 million "new and additional" in line with its promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that Bercy was the one who carried out the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would other member states continue to give if they only have to lend?) and in the negotiations since the developing countries are not completely fooled...
The chapter on early finance is a small one, relatively short-term, compared to the whole climate debate.
But he could be just another grain of sand in the giant machine that is the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that will not be the case.
In any case, it is essential to draw lessons from this first year of early funding.
First, France could announce a change in its accounting for 2011 and 2012 in a spirit of respect for its commitments and fairness with other EU countries.
But above all, France could advance discussions on the issues of long-term financing (another crucial chapter currently being discussed): the question of "additionality" or the way loans are accounted for will not be avoided.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
The hope is therefore in the new environment minister, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement on France's fast start and its vision of 'additionality' and the use of loans would increase the level of international confidence needed to move forward in the talks.
Warning of pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemicals a day, according to a study published Wednesday by the Future Generations Association (formerly the Movement for the Rights and Respect of Future Generations).
The association, which warns that its results "have no statistical significance in view of the small number of samples analysed, but are illustrative of the problem being dealt with", bought between July and September the food normally eaten in four meals and a snack in a day by a child of about ten years in the supermarkets of the Oise and Paris.
These standard meals, including the official recommendations - five fresh fruits and vegetables, three dairy products, and 1.5 liters of water a day - as well as sweets, have been tested by laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals, and other pollutants.
The balance sheet is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, 42 of which are classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five substances classified as certain carcinogens, as well as 37 substances that may act as endocrine disruptors (EDs), according to studies by several institutions such as the International Cancer Research Centre.
"Although the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded in almost all cases, our survey clearly shows that the reality of consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic and/or PE contaminants is a cause for concern", the association notes.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible cancer-causing residues and three confirmed cancer-causing residues as well as nearly 20 residues that may disrupt the hormone system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, was found to contain traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide that is banned in France.
The same applies to Kenyan green beans, which are included in the lunch, and on which the study found traces of a potent insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, minced steak, canned tuna, and even the breadstick and gum were riddled with pesticides and other chemicals.
The tap water was tested for nitrates and chloroform.
For dinner, salmon steak was the "richest" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the examination of the plastic plate used to heat the meal in the microwave was not exempt.
The final risk to the consumer of these "cocktails of contaminants" "is probably underestimated", the study says.
The Ecology Europe-The Greens Alliance (EE-LV) has proposed a moratorium on pesticide use to "combat the urgency of the situation" and to stop "the rise of civilization-diseases".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) reported the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
